SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose in a text and analyze how the author acknowledges and responds to conflicting evidence or viewpoints.
Content: Which set of statements BEST expresses each author's point of view regarding the use of game design in software applications?

A.Choice: The author of passage 1 views the competitive component of games as a fun way to bring people together. The author of passage 2 views the ability to make choices in games as an effective way to meet individual needs.

B.Choice: The author of passage 1 views competition as a main source for the problem of cheating. The author of passage 2 views the competitive element of games as the best way to motivate people to learn.

C.Choice: The author of passage 1 views games as a promising way for businesses to engage consumers and encourage them to share spending habits. The author of passage 2 views games as an enjoyable way to engage learners and make learning more effective.

D.Choice: The author of passage 1 views games as a smart way for businesses and consumers to work together. The author of passage 2 views games as a creative way for business and education to work together and improve learning.

SubTopics: Write informative/explanatory texts to examine a topic and convey ideas, concepts, and information through the selection, organization, and analysis of relevant content.
Content: Write an informational essay comparing and contrasting how the two passages explore the role of games in people's lives. Develop your essay by providing textual evidence from BOTH passages.

:ibox:Manage your time carefully so that you can:

• plan your essay and do some prewriting using your scratch paper.

• write your essay on the lined pages in your test booklet.

:ibox:Be sure to:

• use evidence from BOTH passages.

• avoid over-relying on one passage.
Your written response should be in the form of a multi-paragraph informational essay.

SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative and connotative meanings; analyze the impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone, including allusions to other texts, repetition of words and phrases, and analogies.
Content: In paragraph 3, what does the phrase “shadow of authority” suggest about the relationship between Emma and Miss Taylor?

A.Choice: Miss Taylor had kept constant watch over Emma.

B.Choice: Miss Taylor had been saddened by Emma's attitude.

C.Choice: Miss Taylor had little control of Emma's behavior.

D.Choice: Miss Taylor had been jealous of Emma's carefree life.

SubTopics: Determine the meaning of words and phrases as they are used in a text, including figurative and connotative meanings; analyze the impact of specific word choices on meaning and tone, including allusions to other texts, repetition of words and phrases, and analogies.
Content: How does the author's choice of words in paragraph 4 impact the tone of the passage?

M.Choice: They create a judgemental tone by implying that Emma is uncaring and believes her character is superior to others.

P.Choice: They support an expectant and mildly suspenseful tone by implying that Emma is likely to have her character tested.

R.Choice: They create a reassuring tone by indicating that Emma's strong sense of self will help her overcome challenges.

S.Choice: They support a conceited tone by indicating that Emma's upbringing will ensure her a place in high society.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development over the course of the text, including its relationship to the characters, setting, and plot; provide an objective summary.
Content: Which set of statements best summarizes the passage?

A.Choice: Emma is pleased that her governess has married and has every promise of happiness. However, after the wedding Emma is saddened by the prospect of having only her father to dine with in the evenings.

B.Choice: Emma is pretty, clever, rich, and happy. The wedding of Miss Taylor, her governess, prompts Emma to recall with fondness the loving care and attention Miss Taylor provided over the years.

C.Choice: Emma is a privileged, happy young woman who has had a carefree life. She is faced with the prospect of feeling lonely, perhaps for the first time, when her governess and good friend marries and leaves the household.

D.Choice: Emma is very close to her governess, Miss Taylor, who has been a good friend since Emma was a young child. After Miss Taylor marries, Emma worries about how she will get along with her father, whose personality is very different from Emma's.

SubTopics: Analyze how similarities and differences in the points of view of the audience and the characters create effects such as suspense, humor, or dramatic irony.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What does the reader understand about Emma that she does not understand about herself?

M.Choice: She is self-centered and somewhat spoiled.

P.Choice: She resents having to be the mistress of her father's house.

R.Choice: Miss Taylor is her good friend only because Emma's father pays her.

S.Choice: Her fears of being lonely are unfounded.

Content: Select the quote from the passage that BEST supports the correct answer to Part A.

A.Choice: “Emma Woodhouse, handsome, clever, and rich, with a comfortable home and happy disposition, seemed to unite some of the best blessings of existence; ...” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “The wedding over, ... her father and herself were left to dine together, with no prospect of a third to cheer a long evening.” (paragraph 5)

C.Choice: “She recalled her past kindness — the kindness, the affection of sixteen years — how she had taught and how she had played with her from five years old — ...” (paragraph 6)

D.Choice: “[Miss Taylor] had been a friend and companion such as few possessed:  ... peculiarly interested in herself, in every pleasure, every scheme of hers — ...” (paragraph 6)

SubTopics: Analyze how particular lines of dialogue or incidents in a story or drama propel the action, reveal aspects of a character, or provoke a decision.
Content: Read this sentence from paragraph 6.

:ibox:Mr. Weston was a man of unexceptionable character, easy fortune, suitable age, and pleasant manners; and there was some satisfaction in considering with what self-denying, generous friendship she had always wished and promoted the match; but it was a black morning's work for her.
What does this sentence reveal about Emma's character?

M.Choice: She is jealous of her friend's marriage.

P.Choice: She thinks her friend has made a mistake.

R.Choice: She is determined to remain close to her friend.

S.Choice: She feels she has sacrificed for her friend's happiness.

Content: How does Miss Taylor's approach to her work as Emma's governess relate to the theme of this passage?

A.Choice: Miss Taylor's permissive style leaves Emma unprepared to handle her leaving.

B.Choice: Miss Taylor's changing relationship with Emma reflects Emma's growing maturity.

D.Choice: Miss Taylor's decision to marry gives Emma a chance to grow stronger and more independent.

SubTopics: Delineate and evaluate the argument and specific claims in a text, assessing whether evidence is relevant and sufficient to support the claims and the reasoning is sound.
Content: In paragraph 13, the author states that the chestnut trees' “future is precarious.” Which detail in paragraph 13 supports this claim?

A.Choice: “Here's the curiosity: You can still find American chestnut trees.”

B.Choice: “And throughout the high country, young trees are fairly common.”

C.Choice: “The young trees shoot for the sky, saw-toothed leaves catching the sun, by every indication a sapling on the way to grand stature.”

D.Choice: “It infects and kills most young chestnuts before they are more than a few inches in diameter.”

SubTopics: Determine an author's point of view or purpose in a text and analyze how the author acknowledges and responds to conflicting evidence or viewpoints.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Based on the passage, what is the author's point of view regarding the loss of the American chestnut?

M.Choice: The disappearance of the American chestnut is a great tragedy.

P.Choice: The loss of the chestnut is just one result of a natural process.

R.Choice: The American chestnut had its time in history, but it is now best forgotten.

S.Choice: Botanists and horticulturists did not do enough to save the American chestnut.

Content: Which sentence from the passage BEST supports the correct answer to Part A?

A.Choice: But we still have buildings made from it, and we still have people pulling for it.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “The demise of the American Chestnut is woven into the nation's lore like the tragic wartime death of a beloved family member.” (paragraph 7)

C.Choice: “The blight raced across the Appalachian range at an average rate of 50 miles per year.” (paragraph 8)

D.Choice: “The tree was critical to the building of America and beloved by early horticulturists.” (paragraph 11)

P.Choice: It indicates how fast the fungus could spread.

R.Choice: It illustrates how the spores moved from tree to tree.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development over the course of the text, including its relationship to supporting ideas; provide an objective summary.
Content: Which statement is a central idea of the passage?

A.Choice: The American chestnut has disappeared, but it has been replaced with forests of oak, hickory, and poplar trees.

B.Choice: Despite many efforts to save the American chestnut, millions of trees have died in forests from Georgia to Maine.

C.Choice: The American chestnut had many uses, but a fungus from Asia ruined the chestnut wood and made the chestnuts inedible.

D.Choice: Although the American chestnut was nearly wiped out about 100 years ago by a fungus, some scientists are working to bring the tree back.

SubTopics: Analyze the techniques used to distinguish between and to make connections among individuals, events, or ideas in a text.
Content: How does paragraph 9 connect to the rest of the passage?

M.Choice: It underscores how quickly the blight spread in the eastern states.

P.Choice: It illustrates how a spore is spread from tree to tree.

R.Choice: It describes a major effort that failed to stop the spread of the fungus.

S.Choice: It describes the destruction of chestnut trees like a battle in World War II.

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development over the course of the text, including its relationship to supporting ideas; provide an objective summary.
Content: Which TWO sentences contain information that should be included in a summary of the passage?

A.Choice: “The American chestnut ruled our forests for centuries, but a killer blight made up of microscopic spores needed only 50 years to wipe the giant from the face of North America.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “Once, the springtime canopies of western North Carolina forests were an unmatched floral display, thanks to a tree that nearly vanished.” (paragraph 2)

C.Choice: “Gone was the tree that nurtured Native Americans, passenger pigeons, and pioneer communities.” (paragraph 10)

D.Choice: “In a single year — 1909 — 100,000 cords of chestnut fed five large tanneries in the Asheville region alone.” (paragraph 12)

E.Choice: “But at this very moment, on farms and woodlots scattered across North Carolina and the rest of the native range of the species, an army of volunteers is working on perhaps the most audacious conservation project of our time: bringing back the American chestnut.” (paragraph 14)
